public class TableTest {
    
    private Table table;
    protected Shell shell;
    private static Image iconToUse;
					    
    public static void main(String[] args) {
	
	try {
	    if (args[0].equalsIgnoreCase("green")) {
		iconToUse = new Image(Display.getCurrent(),"greenblob.gif");
	    }
	    else {
		iconToUse = new Image(Display.getCurrent(),"redblob.gif");
	    }
	}
	catch (Exception e) {
	    System.out.println("Usage: TableTest [green|red]");
	    return;
	}
	try {
	    TableTest window = new TableTest();
	    window.open();
	} catch (Exception e) {
	    e.printStackTrace();
	}
    }

    public void open() {
	final Display display = Display.getDefault();
	createContents();
	shell.open();
	shell.layout();
	while (!shell.isDisposed()) {
	    if (!display.readAndDispatch())
		display.sleep();
	}
    }
    
    protected void createContents() {
	shell = new Shell();
	shell.setLayout(new FillLayout());
	
	shell.setText("TableTest");
	final Composite composite = new Composite(shell,SWT.NONE);

	final FillLayout fillLayout = new FillLayout();
	composite.setLayout(fillLayout);

	Button button = new Button(composite,SWT.NONE);

	button.setImage(iconToUse);

	table = new Table(composite, SWT.BORDER);
	table.setLinesVisible(true);
	table.setHeaderVisible(true);

	TableColumn tc = new TableColumn(table,SWT.NONE);
	tc.setWidth(100);
	tc.setText("column heading");

	TableItem ti = new TableItem(table,SWT.NONE);
	ti.setImage(iconToUse);

	composite.setSize(composite.computeSize(SWT.DEFAULT,SWT.DEFAULT));

    }
    
}

Bug.WithStack:
I believe there is a problem with the way that images are handled for
TableItems when running on a Windows system with a reduced colour map.

Specifically, a GIF which is a solid colour that has an RGB value of
(76,178,76) - a sort of off-green - gets rendered as grey when it's
used as the image in a TableItem.  The same GIF file, in the same
application, displays correctly if it is used e.g. as the image for a
Button.

The program below creates a window that contains a button and a table;
for both button and table, I do a "setImage()" specifying the same
Image resource.  If I use a solid red square, the image is rendered
correctly in both cases.  If I use the green, then only the image on
the Button is OK.

This problem has been seen in various cases, all in situations where
the Windows system has minimal colours available, e.g. I can reproduce
it when using a remote desktop to a Windows system and specifying
8-bit colours.  Higher levels of colour don't see the problem.  I see
the problem with 3.0 and 3.1 Eclipse.

I hope this describes the problem OK, I can provide "redblob.gif" and
"greenblob.gif" if you want them.


//////////// TableTest.java //////////////
import org.eclipse.swt.SWT;
import org.eclipse.swt.graphics.Image;
import org.eclipse.swt.layout.FillLayout;
import org.eclipse.swt.widgets.Button;
import org.eclipse.swt.widgets.Composite;
import org.eclipse.swt.widgets.Display;
import org.eclipse.swt.widgets.Shell;
import org.eclipse.swt.widgets.Table;
import org.eclipse.swt.widgets.TableColumn;
import org.eclipse.swt.widgets.TableItem;


public class TableTest {
    
    private Table table;
    protected Shell shell;
    private static Image iconToUse;
					    
    public static void main(String[] args) {
	
	try {
	    if (args[0].equalsIgnoreCase("green")) {
		iconToUse = new Image(Display.getCurrent(),"greenblob.gif");
	    }
	    else {
		iconToUse = new Image(Display.getCurrent(),"redblob.gif");
	    }
	}
	catch (Exception e) {
	    System.out.println("Usage: TableTest [green|red]");
	    return;
	}
	try {
	    TableTest window = new TableTest();
	    window.open();
	} catch (Exception e) {
	    e.printStackTrace();
	}
    }

    public void open() {
	final Display display = Display.getDefault();
	createContents();
	shell.open();
	shell.layout();
	while (!shell.isDisposed()) {
	    if (!display.readAndDispatch())
		display.sleep();
	}
    }
    
    protected void createContents() {
	shell = new Shell();
	shell.setLayout(new FillLayout());
	
	shell.setText("TableTest");
	final Composite composite = new Composite(shell,SWT.NONE);

	final FillLayout fillLayout = new FillLayout();
	composite.setLayout(fillLayout);

	Button button = new Button(composite,SWT.NONE);

	button.setImage(iconToUse);

	table = new Table(composite, SWT.BORDER);
	table.setLinesVisible(true);
	table.setHeaderVisible(true);

	TableColumn tc = new TableColumn(table,SWT.NONE);
	tc.setWidth(100);
	tc.setText("column heading");

	TableItem ti = new TableItem(table,SWT.NONE);
	ti.setImage(iconToUse);

	composite.setSize(composite.computeSize(SWT.DEFAULT,SWT.DEFAULT));

    }
    
}
Could also be that the image list is not created properly for the display.
I'm sorry, we never got to this.  Reduced color displays are more rare these days.

